Jan Adam Gallina [Galina]
(Ctoliby, 13 December 1724 - Ctoliby, 5 January 1773) 

Bohemian composer. He was born into a musical and rich family. He received early studies by his father, the cantor Martin Antonn Gallina (1682-1730), and after his death by other family members. He married the daughter of the governor of the Nov Hrad, Mari Frantikou Haubnerovou. In 1744 he applied for a post at the Ctoliby castle, where he remained as a musician and composer the rest of his life under the patronage of the count Arnot Karel Pachta. Also there he studied with Vclav Jan Kopiva. After the death of the bandmaster Jan Josef Janouek (1717-1750) he was promoted to orchestra director. He attained the title of 'musicae director a aulae praefectus'. Gallina's three brothers were also musicians, among them, Josef Antonn Gallina (1726-1765). As a composer, he wrote several symphonies and religious works only preseved on manuscrits. He died in Ctoliby during the typhus epidemic.
